defs.docs:
Amethyst is a free and open source game engine written in idiomatic
 [Rust][rs] for building video games and interactive multimedia applications.
 The source code is available for download on [GitHub][gh]. See the
 [online book][bk] for a complete guide to using Amethyst.

defs.name: prelude
defs.docs: Contains common types that can be glob-imported (`*`) for convenience.

defs.name: Application
defs.docs:
An Application is the root object of the game engine. It binds the OS
 event loop, state machines, timers and other core components in a central place.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn <P, S, I> (path: P, initial_state: S, init: I) -> Result<Application<'a, T>>
defs.docs:
Creates a new Application with the given initial game state.
 This will create and allocate all the needed resources for
 the event loop of the game engine. It is a shortcut for convenience
 if you need more control over how the engine is configured you should
 be using [build](struct.Application.html#method.build) instead.

defs.name: build
defs.value: fn <P, S> (path: P, initial_state: S) -> Result<ApplicationBuilder<S>>
defs.docs: Creates a new ApplicationBuilder with the given initial game state.

defs.name: run
defs.docs:
Run the gameloop until the game state indicates that the game is no
 longer running. This is done via the `State` returning `Trans::Quit` or
 `Trans::Pop` on the last state in from the stack. See full
 documentation on this in [State](trait.State.html) documentation.

defs.name: ApplicationBuilder
defs.docs:
`ApplicationBuilder` is an interface that allows for creation of an
 [`Application`](struct.Application.html)
 using a custom set of configuration. This is the normal way an
 [`Application`](struct.Application.html)
 object is created.

defs.name: world
defs.docs: Used by bundles to access the world directly

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a new [ApplicationBuilder](struct.ApplicationBuilder.html) instance
 that wraps the initial_state. This is the more verbose way of initializing
 your application if you require specific configuration details to be changed
 away from the default.

defs.name: register
defs.docs:
Registers a component into the entity-component-system. This method
 takes no options other than the component type which is defined
 using a 'turbofish'. See the example for what this looks like.

defs.name: with_resource

defs.name: with_fixed_step_length
defs.docs: Sets the duration between fixed updates, defaults to one sixtieth of a second.

defs.name: ignore_window_close
defs.docs:
Tells the resulting application window to ignore close events if ignore is true.
 This will make your game window unresponsive to operating system close commands.
 Use with caution.

defs.name: Pop
defs.docs:
Remove the active state and resume the next state on the stack or stop
 if there are none.

defs.name: Push
defs.docs: Pause the active state and push a new state onto the stack.

defs.name: Switch
defs.docs: Remove the current state on the stack and insert a different one.

defs.name: Quit
defs.docs: Stop and remove all states and shut down the engine.

defs.name: Trans
defs.docs: Types of state transitions.

defs.name: State
defs.docs: A trait which defines game states that can be used by the state machine.

defs.name: on_start
defs.docs: Executed when the game state begins.

defs.name: on_stop
defs.docs: Executed when the game state exits.

defs.name: on_pause
defs.docs: Executed when a different game state is pushed onto the stack.

defs.name: on_resume
defs.docs: Executed when the application returns to this game state once again.

defs.name: handle_event
defs.docs: Executed on every frame before updating, for use in reacting to events.

defs.name: fixed_update
defs.docs:
Executed repeatedly at stable, predictable intervals (1/60th of a second
 by default).

defs.name: update
defs.docs: Executed on every frame immediately, as fast as the engine will allow.
